attributes.magic: ELF 64-bit LSB executable, x86-64, version 1 (SYSV), dynamically linked, interpreter /lib64/ld-linux-x86-64.so.2, for GNU/Linux 2.6.32, BuildID[sha1]=fd0c6d36f9034c824325a1f59c03df23af22249d, stripped

threat_severity.level_description: Severity HIGH because it was considered trojan. Other contributing factor was that it could not be run in sandboxes.

crowdsourced_ai_results.analysis: This ELF binary is a sophisticated network backdoor/RAT (Remote Access Trojan). It exhibits several definitive malicious behaviors: 1) Singleton control via a lock file at '/var/run/initd.lock'. 2) Standard daemonization through double-forking and setsid() to run in the background. 3) Network packet sniffing using AF_PACKET sockets to monitor for a specific 'magic' trigger sequence (0x4430cd9f and 0x5e142766). 4) A remote command execution (RCE) engine in 'sub_401770' that uses popen() to run shell commands received over the network and redirects stderr to stdout ('2>&1'). The sample also incorporates a full cryptographic library (libtomcrypt) and a custom TLS implementation for secure/encrypted C2 communication, which is common in advanced Linux malware.
